<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. IS IN DEEP FREEZE AFTER LOSING TO ICELAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GRAHAME L. JONES, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The gang that can't shoot straight was off target again Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 Claudio Reyna fired a shot from point-blank range high over the crossbar. Jeff 
Agoos hit a drive that flew just wide of the right post. Hugo Perez watched his 
attempt deflect off the goalkeeper and over the bar. Cobi Jones had no better 
luck with his shot. 
</P>
<P>
 The net result was that Iceland, hardly a soccer power, scored a 2-1 victory 
over the United States before 3,017 at Southwestern College in Chula Vista. 
</P>
<P>
 The match proved one thing: Iceland is closer to being ready for its fall 
qualifying campaign for the 1996 European Championship than the United States 
is to being ready for the World Cup that kicks off in less than two months. 
</P>
<P>
 And the excuse that the Americans did not have their foreign-based stars does 
not wash, either. 
</P>
<P>
 "We were without five or six of our best players," said Iceland Coach Asgeir 
Eliasson, who was diplomatic nonetheless. "They (the U.S. team) did not have 
their full squad. They've got good technique. I'm sure in their World Cup group 
they can be a surprise." 
</P>
<P>
 Not based on Sunday's performance.  
</P>
<P>
 In a match in which Iceland took an early lead when striker Helgi Sigurdsson 
scored on a breakaway in the 20th minute, the U.S. team stumbled about in 
search of direction.  
</P>
<P>
 Matters improved after a tedious first half when Coach Bora Milutinovic made a 
couple of key substitutions. Suddenly, the U.S. team seemed to click a little 
better and, two minutes into the second half, it tied the score. 
</P>
<P>
 Frank Klopas, who until then had been enduring an uncomfortable time as the 
lone striker, latched onto a pass inside the Iceland penalty area, turned and 
fired a low shot that snuck into the net just inside the right post. 
</P>
<P>
 But Iceland then caught the U.S. defense napping in the 86th minute. Forward 
Olaf Pordarson's fierce shot struck U.S. goalkeeper Brad Friedel in the chest 
and rebounded over his head and rolled into the net for a 2-1 lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
