<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; SCHOOL TRANSFERS MIGHT BE LIMITED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAIA DAVIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Beginning in the fall, Ventura parents may send their children to any public 
school in the district, regardless of where they live. 
</P>
<P>
 But there is a catch. 
</P>
<P>
 Under a policy that will be considered by the Ventura Unified School District 
board Tuesday, parents may move their children only to schools that are not 
already full with children from the surrounding neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
 About half of the district's 23 schools are expected to have room next year 
only for students who live within their attendance boundaries, said Arlene 
Miro, director of administrative services. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're not going to deny anybody into a school . . . if there is room after 
the neighborhood kids come into the school," Miro said. 
</P>
<P>
 The proposed policy will also allow the district to limit transfers that 
threaten to upset the racial balance at a school. For instance, if a high 
number of white students are asking to leave a particular school, the district 
may deny the requests if it decides that the transfers would cause too great a 
change in the ratio of whites to minorities. 
</P>
<P>
 A new state law that took effect at the beginning of this year requires all 
school districts to establish policies allowing transfers between schools. But 
the law allows districts to limit transfers to prevent crowding and to maintain 
racial or ethnic balance. 
</P>
<P>
 Parents in the Ventura district are already able to send their children to 
schools outside their neighborhoods, but only if the parent can show a 
compelling reason for the transfer, such as if the new school offers an 
academic course not available elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
 The new school choice policy would allow parents to request such a transfer 
without having to give a reason. 
</P>
<P>
 If the Ventura school board approves the policy Tuesday, parents will be able 
by the end of this month to begin applying for transfers for the next school 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 Applications will be available at all schools in the district, Miro said. MAIA 
DAVIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
