<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUGH LINES; THE GOOD OLD DAYS? SOMEBODY STOLE 'EM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAULA POUNDSTONE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES; Paula Poundstone is a comedian and 
writer who lives in the Los Angeles area. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Even if no one actually steals anything from me ever, for the amount of time, 
money and energy it has cost me to constantly lock and unlock, and be locked 
out of, lock my keys in, alarm and false alarm, and drive two blocks away and 
turn back to make certain I put the alarm on, I might as well have just been 
robbed. 
</P>
<P>
 Sometimes, especially when I can't find my keys, I bitterly reflect on how 
awful the world has become. For a brief and harrowing moment, I become a live 
one for those running for office on the "get tough on crime" platform.  
</P>
<P>
 I wonder how long it will be before we hear a guy on a paid political 
advertisement claim, "If I am elected governor and there are any criminals in 
this state, I'll personally smash their heads in." 
</P>
<P>
 The more I think about it though, the more I realize that things have been 
worse. Take the Old West for example. Now, I'm not exactly a historian, but I 
used to watch "The Big Valley" a lot. People carried guns back then like it was 
a perfectly normal thing. They didn't have the evil NRA then because nobody was 
against guns to begin with. 
</P>
<P>
 Percentage-wise, we couldn't possibly have as much violence as they had back 
then. They were ambushed, their stagecoaches were robbed, they had shoot-outs 
in the middle of the street at noon (right in the middle of the lunch rush), 
they hanged each other from trees, they tarred and feathered people. They used 
to shoot people for cheating at poker.  
</P>
<P>
 My brother used to always get dibs on being the banker in Monopoly in order to 
steal 500s. He never even got yelled at.  
</P>
<P>
 It was definitely a more violent time. Hell, someone could just come up to you 
in a bar and shoot at your feet to get you to dance. You never hear of that in 
the 1990s. We're either less violent or a lot more willing to dance.  
</P>
<P>
 I read once that Geronimo used to bury his victims alive with only their heads 
sticking out, pour molasses over their heads and allow ants to eat them. Geez, 
that went out with tube tops. We're beginning to look like angels, huh? 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 When you think about it, the frightened, angry argument that insists we build 
more jails before we address prevention of the root causes of our violent 
crimes, because we are in a crisis, doesn't make much sense. As it turns out, 
we're always in a crisis.  
</P>
<P>
 I guess Barbra Streisand was right in her "memories" song, which was later 
recorded by Gladys Knight and the Pips, when she said, "What's too painful to 
remember, we simply choose to forget." Still, I'm amazed at how fast her 
tickets went. 
</P>
<P>
 As soon as the news of the poor, stupid American teen-ager who vandalized cars 
in Singapore and has been sentenced to six disfiguring lashes with a bamboo 
cane, administered publicly by a martial arts guy -- as soon as that story came 
to us, people were calling in to God-awful radio shows going on and on about 
that being the kind of justice we need over here. These are the kind of people 
who used to form a posse without the sheriff's permission.  
</P>
<P>
 Punishment has never been the rewarding fix-it we had hoped for. We need to 
deal with the causes of criminal behavior or we'll just keep building tons of 
jails and slowly but surely we'll all fill them. 
</P>
<P>
 The only people on the outside will be a handful of really clever criminals 
and one lonely, honest citizen who will earn a living mowing our lawns, 
bringing in our mail and flipping our porch lights on and off so it looks like 
we're at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
